## WhatsApp Message Extraction — Deep Dive

The `processMessageValue()` method in OrderService handles parsing WhatsApp webhook payloads:

```
INCOMING PAYLOAD STRUCTURE (from WhatsApp Cloud API):

  body.entry[]                              ← array of entry objects
    .changes[]                              ← array of change objects
      .value                                ← WhatsAppMessageValue (the actual message data)
        .contacts[]                         ← sender info
          .profile.name                     ← display name
          .wa_id                            ← WhatsApp ID (phone number)
        .messages[]                         ← message objects
          .id                               ← message ID
          .from                             ← sender phone number
          .type                             ← "text" | "interactive" | "order" | ...
          .text.body                        ← message text (for type="text")
          .interactive.button_reply         ← for type="interactive"
            .id                             ← button ID
            .title                          ← button display title
          .order                            ← for type="order"
            .catalog_id                     ← WhatsApp catalog ID
            .product_items[]               ← ordered items
              .product_retailer_id          ← catalog product ID
              .quantity                     ← item quantity

PRODUCT NAME EXTRACTION (fallback chain):
  1. message.interactive?.button_reply?.title    ← interactive button press
  2. message.text?.body                          ← plain text message content
  3. "Catalog Product"                           ← hardcoded fallback

TOTAL AMOUNT CALCULATION:
  totalAmount = env.payment.defaultAmount × quantity
  (There is no per-product pricing in the WhatsApp flow — it uses a flat default × quantity)
```

---

## Payment Gateway Integration (Easypaisa)

```
  ═══ PAYMENT LINK GENERATION ═══

  PaymentGatewayService.createPaymentLink({ orderReference, amount, currency })
      │
      ├── 1. Build query string via URLSearchParams:
      │       storeId     = env.payment.storeId
      │       orderRef    = orderReference
      │       amount      = amount.toFixed(2)            ← formatted to 2 decimal places
      │       currency    = currency
      │       callbackUrl = env.payment.callbackUrl
      │
      ├── 2. Sign the query string:
      │       signature = HMAC-SHA256(env.payment.hashKey, query.toString())
      │                     .digest("hex")
      │
      ├── 3. Append signature to query:
      │       query.set("signature", signature)
      │
      └── 4. Return full URL:
            return "{env.payment.baseUrl}?{query.toString()}"

  Example final URL:
    https://easypaisa.com/payment?storeId=123&orderRef=ORD-1234-567&amount=1000.00&
    currency=PKR&callbackUrl=https://mysite.com/api/webhooks/payment&
    signature=abc123def456...


  ═══ PAYMENT CALLBACK PARSING ═══

  When Easypaisa POSTs to /api/webhooks/payment, handlePaymentWebhook()
  tries multiple field names for maximum compatibility:

    orderReference:  body.orderReference ?? body.orderRef ?? body.merchantOrderId ?? ""
    gatewayRef:      body.transactionId  ?? body.txnRefNo   ?? body.paymentId       ?? ""
    paymentStatus:   (body.paymentStatus ?? body.status ?? "").toLowerCase()

  Only "paid" and "success" are treated as successful payments.
  Everything else (including empty, "failed", "pending", "cancelled", etc.) → failed path.
```

---

## WhatsApp Cloud API Integration

```
  ═══ WEBHOOK VERIFICATION (one-time setup) ═══

  When configuring the webhook in Meta Business Manager:
    WhatsApp → GET /api/webhooks/whatsapp?hub.mode=subscribe&hub.verify_token={YOUR_TOKEN}&hub.challenge={CODE}

    WebhookController.verifyWhatsAppWebhook:
      → Extracts: req.query["hub.mode"], ["hub.verify_token"], ["hub.challenge"]
      → IF mode === "subscribe" AND token === env.whatsapp.verifyToken
        → res.status(200).send(String(challenge ?? ""))    ← returns challenge as plain text
      → ELSE
        → res.status(403).json({ success: false, error: "Webhook verification failed." })


  ═══ OUTBOUND MESSAGES ═══

  WhatsAppService.sendTextMessage(to, body)
    → Uses Axios instance (configurable via constructor for testing)
    → POST https://graph.facebook.com/{apiVersion}/{phoneNumberId}/messages
    → Headers:
        Authorization: Bearer {WHATSAPP_TOKEN}
        Content-Type: application/json
    → Body: {
        messaging_product: "whatsapp",
        to: "923001234567",                    ← customer's WhatsApp number
        type: "text",
        text: {
          body: "Thank you John. Your order ORD-1234-567 has been created. Payment link: https://..."
        }
      }

  ★ The WhatsAppService constructor accepts an optional AxiosInstance for dependency injection.
    In production, it creates its own Axios instance with the configured baseURL and auth header.
```

---

## Error Handling Patterns

```
  ═══ WEBHOOK CONTROLLER ═══

  handleWhatsAppWebhook:
    → try/catch wraps entire handler
    → On success: 200 { success: true }
    → On error:   500 { success: false, error: error.message || "Unable to process WhatsApp webhook." }

  handlePaymentWebhook:
    → try/catch wraps entire handler
    → On success: 200 { success: true, data: order }
    → On error:   400 { success: false, error: error.message || "Unable to process payment webhook." }
    → ★ Note: payment errors return 400 (client error), WhatsApp errors return 500 (server error)

  ★ Neither webhook handler reads the response body after calling the service.
    If the service throws, the controller catches and returns the error JSON.
    WhatsApp always gets a 200 if processing succeeds (even if there were no messages to process).


  ═══ ADMIN CONTROLLER ═══

  Product create/update:
    → Catches DuplicateProductCatalogIdError → 409 { success: false, error: "A product with ..." }
    → Other errors → 400 { success: false, error: error.message || "Unable to save product." }

  Order get/update:
    → If findOneAndUpdate returns null → 404 { success: false, error: "Order not found." }

  Admin auth login:
    → Invalid credentials → 401 { success: false, error: "Invalid credentials." }


  ═══ MIDDLEWARE ═══

  requireAdminAuth:
    → Cookie auth fails AND API key auth fails → 401 { success: false, error: "Admin authentication required." }


  ═══ ADMIN-AUTH SERVICE ═══

  validateCredentials:
    → Guard: if env.app.adminPassword is falsy (not configured) → return false immediately
    → This prevents login when ADMIN_PASSWORD is not set


  ═══ ORDER SERVICE ═══

  handlePaymentWebhook:
    → If no orderReference can be extracted from the webhook body → throws Error → controller returns 400
    → If updateOrderStatus returns null (order not found), the subsequent transition is skipped
    → WhatsApp messages are only sent if the preceding status update succeeded (null check on each step)

  processMessageValue:
    → If the message has no "from" field → returns early (no error, silently skips)
```

---

## Admin Auth Token Format

```
  Token = "{base64url(payload)}.{base64url(signature)}"

  Payload (JSON):
    {
      "username": "admin",
      "expiresAt": 1712345678000      ← Date.now() + (60 × 60 × 8 × 1000) = 8 hours
    }

  Creation:
    payload_json = JSON.stringify({ username, expiresAt })
    payload_b64  = Buffer.from(payload_json).toString("base64url")
    signature    = crypto.createHmac("sha256", ADMIN_SESSION_SECRET)
                         .update(payload_b64)
                         .digest("base64url")        ← NOTE: base64url, NOT hex
    token        = "${payload_b64}.${signature}"

  Verification steps:
    1. Split token at "."  →  [encodedPayload, signature]
    2. Guard: both parts must exist and be non-empty
    3. Recompute: HMAC-SHA256(secret, encodedPayload).digest("base64url")
    4. timingSafeEqual(computed, provided)  ← constant-time comparison
    5. Decode: JSON.parse(Buffer.from(encodedPayload, "base64url").toString("utf8"))
    6. Verify: payload.username === env.app.adminUsername
    7. Verify: payload.expiresAt > Date.now()
    8. All checks must pass for the token to be valid

  Cookie attributes:
    Name:     admin_session
    Flags:    HttpOnly; SameSite=Lax; Path=/; Max-Age=28800
              + Secure (only if NODE_ENV === "production")

  Clear cookie (logout):
    admin_session=; HttpOnly; SameSite=Lax; Path=/; Max-Age=0
    ★ NOTE: clearCookie does NOT add Secure, even in production.
```

---

## Environment Variables

```
# App
PORT=5000
ADMIN_API_KEY=               ← For server-to-server API auth (x-admin-api-key header)
ADMIN_USERNAME=admin          ← Hardcoded admin username
ADMIN_PASSWORD=               ← Hardcoded admin password (empty = no login possible)
ADMIN_SESSION_SECRET=         ← HMAC signing secret for session cookies (required for token creation)

# Database
MONGODB_URI=mongodb+srv://... ← Required. App will fail to start without it.

# WhatsApp Cloud API
WHATSAPP_API_VERSION=v25.0    ← Facebook Graph API version
WHATSAPP_TOKEN=               ← Permanent access token from Meta Business account
WHATSAPP_PHONE_NUMBER_ID=     ← Phone number ID from Meta Business account
WHATSAPP_VERIFY_TOKEN=        ← Arbitrary string you choose; used once for webhook verification

# Easypaisa Payment Gateway
EASYPAISA_PAYMENT_BASE_URL=   ← Base URL for payment page
EASYPAISA_STORE_ID=           ← Merchant/store identifier
EASYPAISA_HASH_KEY=           ← Secret key for HMAC signing of payment links
EASYPAISA_CALLBACK_URL=       ← Your public URL for payment callbacks (e.g., https://yoursite.com/api/webhooks/payment)

# Defaults
DEFAULT_AMOUNT=1000           ← Default order amount in PKR (used when quantity-based pricing applies)
DEFAULT_CURRENCY=PKR          ← Default currency code
```

